00:13.514 --> 00:18.652
I have a block of cheese in my
colon the size of a grapefruit.

00:18.686 --> 00:20.054
Tony, come on.
Don't be grumpy.

00:20.088 --> 00:23.023
Son of a bitch.

00:23.057 --> 00:24.658
Jesus.

00:24.692 --> 00:26.760
Sometimes I don't
understand you.

00:26.794 --> 00:28.562
I'm so hung over; I just want
to crawl under

00:28.596 --> 00:29.897
the bushes and die.

00:29.930 --> 00:31.599
- Seriously?
- No, I hate this.

00:31.632 --> 00:33.501
Are we there yet?

00:33.534 --> 00:36.870
No, the chalet's, maybe like,
I don't know, half hour?

00:39.207 --> 00:40.908
- Okay.
- Ugh.

00:40.941 --> 00:44.678
- It's amazing.
- Worst episode ever.

00:46.580 --> 00:48.282
♪ I took a walk through this ♪

00:48.316 --> 00:51.619
♪ Beautiful world

00:51.652 --> 00:56.724
♪ Felt the cool rain
on my shoulder ♪

00:56.757 --> 01:00.027
♪ Found something good in this ♪

01:00.060 --> 01:02.963
♪ Beautiful world

01:02.996 --> 01:08.902
♪ I felt the rain
getting colder ♪

01:08.936 --> 01:11.972
- ♪ La, la
- ♪ Sha la, la, la, la

01:12.005 --> 01:14.108
♪ Sha la, la, la, la

01:14.142 --> 01:18.212
- ♪ Sha la, la, la
- Sha la, la, la, la ♪

01:18.246 --> 01:23.083
♪ Sha la, la, la, la, la

01:28.322 --> 01:28.822
♪

01:35.329 --> 01:38.065
The French Alps,

01:38.098 --> 01:39.900
lovely Italians on one side,

01:39.933 --> 01:43.237
but the terrifying Swiss
on the other.

01:43.271 --> 01:44.738
They're close.

01:44.772 --> 01:46.674
Too close for me.

01:46.707 --> 01:49.777
A man with a neurotic childhood
fear of alpine vistas,

01:49.810 --> 01:52.746
yodeling, even cheese
with holes in it.

01:52.780 --> 01:56.750
♪

01:56.784 --> 01:59.820
But my friend
Eric requires payback.

01:59.853 --> 02:03.157
I have, in recent adventures
with him, been unkind.

02:03.191 --> 02:05.259
He grew up in mountains
like this.

02:05.293 --> 02:06.927
He's an expert skier.

02:06.960 --> 02:09.096
This is like home to him,

02:09.128 --> 02:12.366
so I thought it was only fair
he get a chance at payback.

02:12.400 --> 02:16.304
♪

02:16.337 --> 02:18.105
I am not a graceful skier,

02:18.138 --> 02:20.808
but I am an enthusiastic one,

02:20.841 --> 02:23.277
and that's what you come here
for in winter and early spring.

02:23.311 --> 02:26.113
Some of the best
slopes on Earth.

02:26.146 --> 02:29.149
Also cheese, apparently.
Lots of cheese.

02:29.183 --> 02:32.820
♪

02:32.853 --> 02:34.021
I just take your size.

02:34.054 --> 02:35.122
Yes.

02:35.155 --> 02:37.291
Okay.

02:37.325 --> 02:39.660
Bend your knees,
push on the foot.

02:39.693 --> 02:41.128
They decent?

02:41.161 --> 02:42.256
Yeah, they feel good.
That feels good.

02:42.263 --> 02:44.064
- Good?
- Yeah.

02:45.766 --> 02:48.369
You learned to ski
in what, the Pyrenees, right?

02:48.402 --> 02:49.403
- Yeah.
- I learned to ski

02:49.437 --> 02:51.205
in New Jersey.

02:51.239 --> 02:52.806
Eh, it's the same.

02:52.840 --> 02:55.042
Yes.
Well, that's what I always said.

02:58.846 --> 03:01.382
You thought you were going
to the Moon, or what?

03:01.415 --> 03:04.218
Hey warm feet are important.

03:04.252 --> 03:06.854
Nothing's more demoralizing
than cold, wet feet.

03:06.887 --> 03:08.349
You'll be bitching
in those things; yeah, you'll...

03:08.356 --> 03:10.891
- No, man.
- You'll look... you'll look cool.

03:10.924 --> 03:13.327
That's gonna be...
These are gonna be like sponges.

03:13.361 --> 03:15.696
- You wish me bad luck.
- No, I don't.

03:15.729 --> 03:17.358
I just think you should
have proper footwear, man.

03:17.365 --> 03:21.001
Prior preparation prevents
piss-poor performance.

03:24.037 --> 03:26.073
♪

03:26.106 --> 03:29.843
Ski log, day one.
Conditions are not ideal.

03:29.877 --> 03:32.012
It's thick powder
and zero visibility.

03:32.045 --> 03:35.716
♪

03:35.749 --> 03:38.786
Plus, I haven't skied in years,

03:38.819 --> 03:41.689
so it hurts... bad.

03:41.722 --> 03:42.222
♪

03:46.960 --> 03:49.697
But God bless the French,
they can't go too long,

03:49.730 --> 03:53.334
not even down a mountain,
without eating well.

03:54.234 --> 03:56.136
I gotta tell you,
I'm not impressed

03:56.169 --> 03:57.798
with my performance
on that hill; I was dying.

03:57.805 --> 03:59.307
Today's challenging.
I mean, look.

03:59.340 --> 04:03.110
It... it's about 3 feet
of fresh snow.

04:03.143 --> 04:06.480
The visibility was okay,
barely okay.

04:06.514 --> 04:08.949
A year ago, at this time,
I was a killing machine.

04:08.982 --> 04:10.451
Now, I was like...

04:10.484 --> 04:12.252
I was seeing stars,
I mean, I, I...

04:12.286 --> 04:13.454
No, it was the altitude.

04:16.490 --> 04:16.990
♪

04:26.300 --> 04:29.503
And some extravagant,
fantastic, uh, red wine.

04:29.537 --> 04:31.138
We blow up the budget?

04:31.171 --> 04:33.106
Kill 'em.

04:33.140 --> 04:34.775
- Kill it?
- Kill 'em.

04:34.808 --> 04:36.276
Okay, okay, all done.

04:36.310 --> 04:38.479
Definitely the '66 Latour.
How much is it?

04:38.512 --> 04:39.847
Is it... is it expensive enough?

04:39.880 --> 04:42.516
- Yeah.
- Oh, yeah.

04:42.550 --> 04:44.251
- They're gonna love you.
- We deserve it.

04:47.287 --> 04:50.791
♪

04:50.824 --> 04:53.327
- Oh, it's good.
- Right, this is good, huh?

04:53.361 --> 04:56.864
Well worth the expense
to someone else.

04:56.897 --> 04:58.332
This is the bigger name.

04:58.366 --> 04:59.867
We're gonna have a week
of good food,

04:59.900 --> 05:01.835
good wine, some ski, right?

05:01.869 --> 05:05.305
So, what, what are the
specialite ...of the region?

05:05.339 --> 05:07.441
So, they do the raclettes.

05:07.475 --> 05:09.109
- Cheese.
- You know like, yeah, cheese,

05:09.142 --> 05:10.444
- Right.
- The fondue.

05:10.478 --> 05:12.880
- That's cheese.
- Da dufflets.

05:12.913 --> 05:15.015
- That's cheese.
- Yep.

05:15.048 --> 05:16.884
I don't know.

05:16.917 --> 05:18.812
- That's not bad; I like cheese.
- Yeah, I like stews.

05:18.819 --> 05:21.489
They make a lot of stews too.
Yeah, of what animals?

05:21.522 --> 05:22.956
Mostly beef.

05:22.990 --> 05:24.291
- Yeah?
- Yeah.

05:24.324 --> 05:25.526
- A lot of cows up here?
- Yeah.

05:25.559 --> 05:28.328
I like cows... to eat.

05:28.362 --> 05:30.130
Yeah, to eat, of course.

05:30.163 --> 05:31.799
Don't much like 'em personally.

05:31.832 --> 05:33.834
♪

05:33.867 --> 05:35.903
Where I learned to ski,
we were lucky

05:35.936 --> 05:38.164
to get lukewarm chicken fingers
and a Bud Light at the lodge.

05:38.171 --> 05:42.309
Here, we start with
pan-seared foie gras.

05:42.342 --> 05:44.077
Wow.

05:44.111 --> 05:46.013
- That's fancy, huh?
- All right.

05:46.046 --> 05:48.482
I mean, why don't you eat that
on the ski slope? Seriously.

05:48.516 --> 05:50.518
♪

05:50.551 --> 05:54.354
For the main, a loin of veal,
gently seared and pan-roasted.

05:54.388 --> 05:57.024
Joined by a wild mushroom sauce,

05:57.057 --> 05:59.527
and a pretty little medley
of vegetables.

05:59.560 --> 06:02.062
- Whoa.
- Looking good.

06:02.095 --> 06:03.897
Hoo-hoo.

06:03.931 --> 06:06.900
How is it?
It's really good.

06:06.934 --> 06:10.404
It's also... I wanted you to know
this... humanely raised veal,

06:10.438 --> 06:14.442
free-range, died in its sleep.

06:14.475 --> 06:17.411
I disagree with that,
but I will eat it.

06:17.445 --> 06:20.013
Just trying to make you feel
better about the world.

06:20.047 --> 06:22.450
I'm all over the cheese course
like a one-man army.

06:22.483 --> 06:25.519
Tomme de chevre,
tomme de savoie et piment,

06:25.553 --> 06:28.288
fromage de chevre
et creme de ren.

06:28.321 --> 06:30.357
That's from, like, a cow.

06:30.390 --> 06:32.960
Everybody has blood
on their hands, Eric, everybody.

06:32.993 --> 06:35.395
- I do too.
- Right, we all do.

06:35.429 --> 06:36.930
- I do too.
- The clothes we wear,

06:36.964 --> 06:38.866
the air we breathe.

06:38.899 --> 06:40.434
Everything we do
is built on the backs

06:40.468 --> 06:43.571
of suffering people
and dying animals.

06:43.604 --> 06:45.072
I agree.

06:45.105 --> 06:46.874
We wallow in blood.

06:49.910 --> 06:50.410
♪

06:56.917 --> 06:58.986
Ski log, day two.

06:59.019 --> 07:03.390
Yesterday, Chef Ripert showed
no mercy on the mountain.

07:03.423 --> 07:06.159
Today, conditions
are more to my liking.

07:06.193 --> 07:08.261
A small wager
might have been made.

07:08.295 --> 07:11.431
Loser might have to eat
at Johnny Rockets.

07:11.465 --> 07:13.901
Today it is on.

07:13.934 --> 07:15.068
Ready?

07:15.102 --> 07:18.405
Yeah.

07:18.438 --> 07:20.641
One, two, three.

07:23.677 --> 07:24.177
♪

08:22.670 --> 08:23.170
♪

08:27.775 --> 08:31.144
The title for your biography,
for your bio pic:

08:31.178 --> 08:33.647
"32 Yolks: The Revenge,"
or whatever we're calling it.

08:33.681 --> 08:37.350
"64 Yolks,"
or "For a Few Yolks More."

08:37.384 --> 08:39.653
Well, that'll be the sequel.
"A Fistfull of Yolks."

08:39.687 --> 08:41.354
Okay, that's what we'll call it.

08:41.388 --> 08:42.683
We have to change it
to a more manly title.

08:42.690 --> 08:44.057
- It's... it's...
- "32 Yolks" is...

08:44.091 --> 08:45.492
Now it's becoming your book.

08:45.525 --> 08:47.227
You're changing it; you're...

08:47.260 --> 08:48.996
Welcome to Hollywood, my friend.

08:52.600 --> 08:54.501
The Cremery.

08:54.534 --> 08:56.737
A special place at the bottom
of the mountain.

08:56.770 --> 09:00.774
Croute with morilles,
and cream, lots of cream.

09:00.808 --> 09:04.678
I didn't expect that;
that's really good.

09:04.712 --> 09:06.213
Yeah.

09:06.246 --> 09:07.540
We're eating bread
and mushrooms...

09:07.547 --> 09:08.515
- Right.
- Cheese.

09:08.548 --> 09:09.683
There's no meat in this.

09:09.717 --> 09:11.451
No, there's no meat.

09:11.484 --> 09:13.520
I'm, like, practically
like Gandhi at this point.

09:13.553 --> 09:14.053
♪

09:19.492 --> 09:21.194
I'm not drastic.

09:21.228 --> 09:23.056
I'm not saying, "Don't eat meat,
become a vegan."

09:23.063 --> 09:24.765
I'm saying, "Let's eat less
meat."

09:24.798 --> 09:26.566
You just think it's better
for the planet?

09:26.600 --> 09:29.737
It's good for the planet;
it's good for our bodies.

09:29.770 --> 09:31.639
I'll... I'll stand outside
the Bourdeau Dan.

09:31.672 --> 09:33.440
I'll tell all
your customers that.

09:33.473 --> 09:36.109
"You know, this fish thing,
you should really,

09:36.143 --> 09:38.278
you should eat some vegetables."

09:38.311 --> 09:38.811
♪

09:44.317 --> 09:47.487
Bovine flatulence is a major
source of carbon dioxide.

09:47.520 --> 09:50.090
Yes. It's the biggest
one in the world.

09:50.123 --> 09:51.417
No, not the biggest one
in the world.

09:51.424 --> 09:53.226
- Yes.
- Bovine flatulence?

09:53.260 --> 09:57.430
Yes, bigger than cars,
bigger than anything else.

09:57.464 --> 09:59.733
See, this is why
we should eat meat.

09:59.767 --> 10:02.069
We're saving the planet;
we're gonna kill these things.

10:02.102 --> 10:04.471
♪

10:04.504 --> 10:06.674
We're ripping a hole
in the ozone layer.

10:06.707 --> 10:08.408
Plus, it stinks.

10:08.441 --> 10:09.677
You are a lost... lost case.

10:15.783 --> 10:17.517
What does she want?

10:17.550 --> 10:20.153
She said she hopes you're
very hungry, because...

10:20.187 --> 10:21.588
Uh-oh.

10:21.621 --> 10:24.124
What's coming is serious.

10:27.160 --> 10:28.295
♪

10:28.328 --> 10:30.330
Farcante.

10:30.363 --> 10:31.792
I think that means "cannonball
of goodness" in French,

10:31.799 --> 10:33.701
because it's a big, heavy,

10:33.734 --> 10:36.136
albeit yet thoroughly
delicious loaf of potato,

10:36.169 --> 10:38.438
bacon, dried fruit, and cream

10:38.471 --> 10:42.342
slowly steamed in a bain-marie.

10:42.375 --> 10:44.477
♪

10:44.511 --> 10:46.572
This meal is a foreshadowing
of the kind of light spa food

10:46.579 --> 10:50.684
that will become a regular
feature of our time in the Alps.

10:50.718 --> 10:53.821
- Whoa.
- Whoa.

10:55.488 --> 10:58.491
We have to finish that.

10:58.525 --> 11:02.129
It's like a...
It's like a volcano.

11:02.162 --> 11:03.663
Look at this.

11:03.697 --> 11:07.367
You can put the dried
apricots or plums as well.

11:07.400 --> 11:09.236
So, it's a bit sweet and salty.

11:09.269 --> 11:10.403
It's...
It's very good.

11:10.437 --> 11:11.404
It's really good.

11:11.438 --> 11:14.674
♪

11:14.708 --> 11:17.811
You put that on a "Man versus
Food," food wins.

11:17.845 --> 11:22.482
Can Eric Ripert eat
the entire farcante in one hour?

11:22.515 --> 11:25.352
If you can save the world,
could you eat that?

11:25.385 --> 11:27.520
No, if you could save a puppy,
could you eat that?

11:27.554 --> 11:29.489
- To save a puppy? Yeah.
- The whole thing.

11:29.522 --> 11:30.751
You'd eat the whole thing
to save a puppy?

11:30.758 --> 11:33.426
Yeah.

11:33.460 --> 11:34.862
Get me a puppy.

11:50.443 --> 11:50.943
♪

12:01.254 --> 12:04.624
Ah, nature,
the rustic charms of the farm,

12:04.657 --> 12:06.794
proximity to one's ingredients,

12:06.827 --> 12:10.697
the smell of fresh grass,
manure, livestock.

12:10.730 --> 12:14.968
I love it.
No, actually, that's Eric.

12:15.002 --> 12:16.904
I didn't mean to be
presumptuous,

12:16.937 --> 12:18.564
but last night after dinner,
I went back to my room,

12:18.571 --> 12:20.707
and I whipped up
a little pâté for us.

12:20.740 --> 12:22.709
Yes, of course.

12:22.742 --> 12:24.237
I thought the croûte came out
pretty well, don't you think?

12:24.244 --> 12:25.879
- Yep.
- I mean, not bad for

12:25.913 --> 12:27.774
a little microwave in my room.
With some Génépi.

12:27.781 --> 12:30.250
Because I know you're a man
of expensive tastes,

12:30.283 --> 12:31.985
I foraged for truffles
this morning.

12:32.019 --> 12:36.323
I rented a truffle-seeking pig
and managed to dig this guy up.

12:36.356 --> 12:37.757
That's pretty nice.

12:37.791 --> 12:39.459
Perhaps you want to do the
honors? The...

12:39.492 --> 12:40.787
- Yeah.
- Wow, look at that knife work.

12:40.794 --> 12:42.262
You should be a chef.

12:43.831 --> 12:45.833
A nice cheese selection
from this very farm.

12:45.866 --> 12:47.427
- Yes, I guess.
- The process that we will be

12:47.434 --> 12:48.501
helping along today.

12:51.438 --> 12:53.740
I'm excited about that
as an experience.

12:53.773 --> 12:55.642
I mean, everything is
an experience today.

12:55.675 --> 12:58.445
So is a colonoscopy, but...

12:58.478 --> 13:00.480
So you ever milked a cow before?

13:00.513 --> 13:03.316
I loved going to the farm
when I was a kid.

13:03.350 --> 13:05.318
- Yeah?
- They, like, they had 20 cows.

13:05.352 --> 13:07.787
In the farming community
in which you grew up,

13:07.821 --> 13:11.424
did kids at school
ever brag about sort of...

13:11.458 --> 13:13.319
I don't know how you describe
this for a family audience...

13:13.326 --> 13:15.762
But inappropriate
contact with...

13:15.795 --> 13:17.430
- No.
- With farm animals?

13:17.464 --> 13:18.765
- No.
- Really? Never?

13:18.798 --> 13:20.433
- No.
- So if I made, like,

13:20.467 --> 13:21.962
a grass smoothie and poured
it on your crotch,

13:21.969 --> 13:23.603
I think it would be
pretty funny.

13:23.636 --> 13:25.605
- It wouldn't.
- If no one was watching.

13:25.638 --> 13:27.540
Yeah, no one is watching.

13:29.409 --> 13:32.279
This scene is gone.
This scene doesn't exist.

13:37.084 --> 13:38.678
Don't do that while
I'm milking you, man.

13:38.685 --> 13:41.021
She's like...

13:41.054 --> 13:44.324
Now, the milking thing, I...
I have some concerns.

13:44.357 --> 13:46.459
I'm afraid.

13:46.493 --> 13:47.724
- Are you?
- I'm a little afraid.

13:50.763 --> 13:54.968
I... I think they sense that I,
you know, my Jersey roots

13:55.002 --> 13:58.738
as opposed to, you know,
your country ass, you know?

13:58.771 --> 14:01.108
They know you; they recognize
you as one of theirs.

14:02.409 --> 14:05.913
Hello, Nadine. Huh?

14:05.946 --> 14:08.381
You don't like Tony, huh?

14:08.415 --> 14:11.351
Don't let him do it.

14:11.384 --> 14:13.420
Kick him in the balls.

14:16.456 --> 14:17.657
♪

14:17.690 --> 14:20.593
I give you $1,000 cash

14:20.627 --> 14:22.662
if you can get
some milk out of this cow.

14:22.695 --> 14:24.664
You'll give me a 1,000 bucks?

14:24.697 --> 14:26.499
Okay, now we're
talking, my friend.

14:26.533 --> 14:27.767
Yeah.

14:27.800 --> 14:29.102
Show me how it's done, farm boy.

14:29.136 --> 14:32.605
- Oh, he's gonna show us.
- Okay.

14:32.639 --> 14:34.007
Okay, I can do that.

14:34.041 --> 14:35.008
You see how he does?

14:35.042 --> 14:36.576
I think so. Okay.

14:36.609 --> 14:38.645
- Okay?
- You first.

14:40.047 --> 14:42.849
Okay.

14:42.882 --> 14:45.518
Oh, there you go.

14:45.552 --> 14:47.547
We should be playing,
like, some '70s music, you know.

14:47.554 --> 14:48.888
♪ Un-chicka-un-chicka-un

14:48.922 --> 14:50.623
Okay, save some for me.

14:50.657 --> 14:54.561
Come on, man, that's my $1,000
going in that pail.

14:54.594 --> 14:56.396
- Okay, your turn.
- All right.

14:56.429 --> 14:57.890
Watch how it's done.
Yeah. Jeez, I'm telling you.

14:57.897 --> 15:02.469
- Go ahead.
- Okay. Oh, it's soft.

15:02.502 --> 15:03.770
Hey, what's that called?

15:03.803 --> 15:06.940
That's called $1,000, my friend.

15:08.841 --> 15:10.978
Oh, that's strangely satisfying.

15:14.982 --> 15:16.049
That's my grand.

15:17.650 --> 15:19.619
I feel like a... a champion.

15:19.652 --> 15:21.788
You don't want to do
a goat, huh?

15:21.821 --> 15:23.056
So to speak.

15:23.090 --> 15:24.624
I mean, yes.

15:24.657 --> 15:25.918
I think we learned
something here today.

15:25.925 --> 15:27.660
Yeah. Do it quickly.

15:32.932 --> 15:36.736
♪

15:36.769 --> 15:39.906
Cheese. Don't get me wrong.
I love cheese. I adore it.

15:39.939 --> 15:42.575
But it's day
three of nonstop cheese,

15:42.609 --> 15:44.511
and we haven't even
scratched the surface

15:44.544 --> 15:47.114
of the many wondrous
specialties of the region.

15:47.147 --> 15:50.783
Hotel Du Buet has been
around for many years.

15:50.817 --> 15:53.186
One comes here for the cheese.

15:53.220 --> 15:55.955
In this case,
the iconic raclette,

15:55.989 --> 15:58.658
and the equally iconic fondue.

15:58.691 --> 16:00.460
Hello, can I have
a drink with you?

16:00.493 --> 16:01.661
Please.

16:01.694 --> 16:03.130
Cheers.

16:03.163 --> 16:05.032
Marianne Chanel and her siblings

16:05.065 --> 16:07.834
are the third generation
of her family to run this place.

16:07.867 --> 16:09.769
So this is a fa...
A family business?

16:09.802 --> 16:11.804
- Yes.
- For how many years?

16:11.838 --> 16:15.108
- Soon 130 years.
- 130 years?

16:15.142 --> 16:17.644
So, in the family,
the whole time?

16:17.677 --> 16:19.012
Yes, it's my great granddad.

16:19.046 --> 16:20.113
Great grandfather?

16:23.850 --> 16:24.910
So, you're gonna have
to help us.

16:24.917 --> 16:26.719
I explain.

16:26.753 --> 16:28.014
Finally, raclette.
I've been waiting for this.

16:28.021 --> 16:30.623
I know.

16:30.657 --> 16:32.959
Would you like it direct
on your potatoes?

16:32.992 --> 16:34.961
Please. Oh, it bubbles.

16:34.994 --> 16:37.130
- Yeah.
- I cut with this part.

16:37.164 --> 16:40.133
♪

16:40.167 --> 16:43.136
Oh, man, yeah. That's... whoa.

16:45.605 --> 16:47.140
- Yeah, man, go for it.
- You wanna try?

16:47.174 --> 16:48.508
No, no, go... go for it, big
boy.

16:48.541 --> 16:50.677
All right. Here we go.

16:53.046 --> 16:54.614
Okay.

16:57.250 --> 17:00.520
Uh... is there a future for him
in the restaurant business?

17:00.553 --> 17:02.055
I'm not so sure.

17:02.089 --> 17:03.890
Normal humans do not usually
follow

17:03.923 --> 17:05.992
multiple wads of oozing cheese

17:06.025 --> 17:09.229
melted over potatoes with a
molten pot of more cheese.

17:09.262 --> 17:10.762
So, you excited?

17:10.797 --> 17:13.066
Finally, your fondue?
Yeah.

17:13.099 --> 17:15.768
But we are no ordinary men.

17:15.801 --> 17:19.005
We are Titans. We are Centurions
of dairy products.

17:19.038 --> 17:21.574
- See the fondue?
- Okay, let's do the fondue.

17:21.608 --> 17:24.077
- Do some eights slowly.
- Figure eight.

17:24.111 --> 17:27.012
Eight on the bottom.
You touch the bottom.

17:27.046 --> 17:28.915
But not too... tong,
tong, tong, like this.

17:28.948 --> 17:31.118
Yes, yes, yes.

17:31.151 --> 17:33.686
- Oh, man, that's good.
- That's what I said.

17:33.720 --> 17:36.055
When you do that
to the end of the fondue...

17:36.089 --> 17:38.525
- Right.
- The fondue's perfect.

17:38.558 --> 17:41.060
You know, you should know
he bet me...

17:41.094 --> 17:44.897
He bet me $1,000 today
that I could not milk a cow.

17:44.931 --> 17:47.066
- And you do?
- I did.

17:47.100 --> 17:48.601
- Yeah.
- Victory.

17:48.635 --> 17:50.737
Look, I know what to do
with a cow.

17:50.770 --> 17:51.964
I know what you do is,
you gonna...

17:51.971 --> 17:53.640
You put it in your fridge.

17:53.673 --> 17:54.774
Exactly, right, right.

17:54.807 --> 17:56.008
You are so sweet.

18:00.347 --> 18:02.048
How can you do it?

18:02.081 --> 18:03.950
Can I do what?

18:03.983 --> 18:05.745
I mean, to be surrounded by
so much of this great cheese.

18:05.752 --> 18:08.888
Well, we ate about
a pound of cheese each.

18:08.921 --> 18:11.224
You're gonna have
a big cannonball of crap

18:11.258 --> 18:14.227
lodged up your butt
like a baby head.

18:16.129 --> 18:17.964
The size
of a freaking baby head.

18:17.997 --> 18:20.267
You will understand
the agony of delivery.

18:20.300 --> 18:22.302
We are not leaving this table...

18:22.335 --> 18:24.604
Well, we are, because
there's a bunch of drunk,

18:24.637 --> 18:26.906
horny mountaineers
coming in later.

18:26.939 --> 18:28.908
Oh, we're gonna party
with them, happily.

18:28.941 --> 18:31.178
No, because I believe there
might be yodeling involved.

18:47.794 --> 18:49.179
- My God.
- I'm not worried about it.

18:49.196 --> 18:50.197
I'll be fine.

18:53.966 --> 18:56.102
Oh, whoa, whoa, watch this.

18:56.135 --> 18:58.037
Okay, here goes the egg.

18:59.839 --> 19:02.309
Oh, now we're getting serious.

19:07.347 --> 19:10.317
- Can I try?
- Yup.

19:10.350 --> 19:12.151
- Oh, man, that's good.
- It's different, huh?

19:12.185 --> 19:14.187
- Totally.
- Oh, appreciate it.

19:43.750 --> 19:44.250
♪

19:59.966 --> 20:04.203
- Holy Christ.
- What?

20:04.237 --> 20:07.106
It's flat;
we haven't started yet.

20:07.139 --> 20:09.342
Why do people do this?

20:09.376 --> 20:14.281
You do that to stay in shape,
to enjoy nature.

20:14.314 --> 20:16.949
- This is not a sport.
- Not a sport, man.

20:16.983 --> 20:20.887
- This is a death sentence.
- We came from New York.

20:20.920 --> 20:24.857
Look at the difference.
It's so peaceful.

20:24.891 --> 20:26.426
You can go do this
is Central Park.

20:26.459 --> 20:28.861
Yeah, you can do that
in Central Park.

20:28.895 --> 20:33.199
- But, why would you?
- Ah, for fun.

20:33.232 --> 20:35.735
This is for fun.
We're doing that for fun, Tony.

20:38.237 --> 20:40.773
This is fun
like chlamydia is fun.

20:40.807 --> 20:43.209
We haven't even started
to go up.

20:44.911 --> 20:49.782
Okay, now, that's...
That's doing it exercise.

20:49.816 --> 20:51.884
♪

20:51.918 --> 20:54.153
Oh, hell.

21:00.460 --> 21:00.960
♪

21:06.299 --> 21:08.735
Every chef needs a mentor.

21:08.768 --> 21:11.504
In the life and career
of Eric Ripert,

21:11.538 --> 21:14.507
it was Maurice Guillot
who filled that role,

21:14.541 --> 21:16.443
who took a young,
fresh-faced cook

21:16.476 --> 21:19.078
from the mean streets of Antibes

21:19.111 --> 21:20.272
and turned him into the hardened

21:20.279 --> 21:22.148
professional he is today.

22:15.602 --> 22:17.537
Breakfast.

22:17.570 --> 22:20.306
Bonjour.

22:20.339 --> 22:21.841
- Bonjour.
- Bonjour.

22:49.402 --> 22:51.203
They said they'd cook lunch,

22:51.237 --> 22:53.005
which sounded like a sweet deal

22:53.039 --> 22:54.607
considering what's on the menu.

22:56.976 --> 22:58.411
Ahh.

22:59.479 --> 23:01.514
Cheers.

23:01.548 --> 23:04.551
Start with heaping spoons full
of the finest osetra caviar.

23:04.584 --> 23:06.519
So, when you were from the east,

23:06.553 --> 23:08.921
on a scale of 1 to 10,
how good are...

23:08.955 --> 23:10.557
- Minus 2.
- Minus 2,

23:10.590 --> 23:12.224
and you only ended up
in the kitchen

23:12.258 --> 23:13.960
because you were
such a shit waiter, right?

23:13.993 --> 23:16.095
Yeah, no, but I wanted
to be in the kitchen.

23:16.128 --> 23:19.432
After graduation,
I was in Paris with my suitcase.

23:19.466 --> 23:23.536
I was 17 years old,
and then I see that guy.

23:23.570 --> 23:26.238
Maybe some asparagus,
upon which one nestles

23:26.272 --> 23:28.641
a poached egg,

23:28.675 --> 23:31.110
a freshly frothed zabaione,

23:31.143 --> 23:34.914
and an obscenely generous pile
of black truffle shavings.

23:34.947 --> 23:38.918
I actually... I like
a little zabaione.

23:38.951 --> 23:40.920
Egg on egg, man.
Nothing beats it.

23:43.255 --> 23:44.991
Ridiculous.

23:45.024 --> 23:46.318
I don't know why people
mistake me for you.

23:46.325 --> 23:47.994
Because they see us
on TV together.

23:48.027 --> 23:49.962
We both have the white hair,
and people can say,

23:49.996 --> 23:52.231
"Oh, I love your restaurant;
it's so good, Le Bernardin.

23:52.264 --> 23:54.166
"Le Bernardin,
I love your restaurant.

23:54.200 --> 23:57.937
It's great, the fish,
it's wonderful."

23:57.970 --> 23:59.438
You know what I always say?

23:59.472 --> 24:01.007
No, I always say, you know,

24:01.040 --> 24:03.142
"Can you believe
all our fish is frozen."

24:03.175 --> 24:04.677
No, he does.

24:04.711 --> 24:06.312
He's not joking.

24:11.551 --> 24:16.355
Steak au poivre with some
fresh morel and new potatoes.

24:16.388 --> 24:18.591
So what was 32 yolks again?

24:18.625 --> 24:20.426
What was the... that's the recipe?

24:20.459 --> 24:21.487
Yeah, for the hollandaise.
For his hollandaise.

24:21.494 --> 24:23.195
32... 32 yolks.

24:23.229 --> 24:25.097
Yeah, to make the
hollandaise for him.

24:25.131 --> 24:28.334
- No, it's an excellent book.
- Thank you, Tony.

24:28.367 --> 24:32.271
My favorite part is
when you're in prison

24:32.304 --> 24:34.106
in the south of France.

24:34.140 --> 24:36.108
They force him to bite the heads
off live chickens

24:36.142 --> 24:37.677
for the amusement
of the other convicts.

24:37.710 --> 24:39.345
- We did...
- That was a good scene,

24:39.378 --> 24:40.573
or was that "Midnight Express?"
I forget.

24:40.580 --> 24:42.014
It was "Midnight Express."

24:45.051 --> 24:47.319
♪

24:47.353 --> 24:50.222
How many years
did you guys work together?

24:50.256 --> 24:52.158
Actually, a long time.

24:52.191 --> 24:55.327
From day one of my career,
to when I left to America.

24:55.361 --> 24:57.496
Very long time.

24:59.666 --> 25:02.468
Why did you go to America and
leave your ancestral home land?

25:02.501 --> 25:07.139
Robichon sent me to America.
I wanted to go to Brazil,

25:07.173 --> 25:09.308
and then he looked at me
and smiled and he said,

25:09.341 --> 25:11.010
"Uh, I can't send you to Brazil.

25:11.043 --> 25:12.679
You're not gonna cook
anything there."

25:12.712 --> 25:14.747
- Right.
- Actually, Robichon helped me

25:14.781 --> 25:16.549
to come to America.
He found me the job.

25:16.583 --> 25:17.083
♪

25:22.388 --> 25:25.324
Yeah, what would you have been
if you'd failed as a...

25:25.357 --> 25:26.492
As an aspiring chef?

25:26.525 --> 25:28.194
What was your fallback position?

25:28.227 --> 25:29.996
I wanted to be a forest ranger.

25:30.029 --> 25:31.598
- Forest ranger?
- Yeah.

25:31.631 --> 25:33.332
Why? You like nature
or something?

25:33.365 --> 25:35.201
- Yeah.
- What was it, the uniform?

25:35.234 --> 25:37.236
You like the uniform?
The shorts... they get shorts,

25:37.269 --> 25:39.505
and a little hat
like Smokey the Bear.

25:40.640 --> 25:44.343
♪

25:44.376 --> 25:46.345
But you're not
an outdoorsman at all.

25:46.378 --> 25:48.414
- What do you mean?
- You don't fish.

25:48.447 --> 25:51.684
No, because I don't
wanna catch fish.

25:53.720 --> 25:55.688
We'll leave that where it is.

25:55.722 --> 25:58.691
You've probably killed more
fish over the telephone than...

25:58.725 --> 26:00.559
A good fisherman.

26:00.593 --> 26:02.128
They are dead already.

26:02.161 --> 26:04.463
No, they kill them for you.

26:04.496 --> 26:06.699
Don't say that.

26:06.733 --> 26:09.201
You're like Scarface.

26:09.235 --> 26:10.663
Don't say that or I give you
a lot of salad.

26:10.670 --> 26:12.271
Oh.

26:12.304 --> 26:12.804
♪

26:27.519 --> 26:29.421
♪

26:29.455 --> 26:33.225
These mountains
are majestic and beautiful.

26:33.259 --> 26:35.728
You can walk them, take pictures
of them.

26:35.762 --> 26:37.764
You can ski down them.

26:37.797 --> 26:39.465
They can also kill you.

26:39.498 --> 26:39.998
♪

26:44.303 --> 26:46.138
So when shit gets bad,

26:46.172 --> 26:48.340
and you find yourself
a tangle of busted bones

26:48.374 --> 26:50.242
and torn flesh,

26:50.276 --> 26:52.645
having slid off
a lonely, high-altitude piece,

26:52.679 --> 26:55.682
it's people like Laurent
Langoisseur

26:55.715 --> 26:59.518
of La Compagnie du Mont-Blanc
who come and save you.

26:59.551 --> 27:02.789
Sonia Popoff works for Peloton
de Gendarmerie

27:02.822 --> 27:04.757
de Haute Montagne.

27:04.791 --> 27:09.128
She's who you call
when things are really bad.

27:09.161 --> 27:11.630
This was Eric's life dream
as a young man, to be a...

27:11.664 --> 27:14.333
- Yeah.
- A park ranger up in the Alps,

27:14.366 --> 27:16.195
or in the mountains; this is
what he wanted to do as a...

27:16.202 --> 27:17.603
- I wanted to be...
- As a young man.

27:17.636 --> 27:19.438
- I wanted to be you.
- Let's face it.

27:19.471 --> 27:21.841
Your career as a chef is coming
to a... coming to an end.

27:21.874 --> 27:23.776
You just turned 52.

27:23.810 --> 27:26.445
Is it too late for him to start?

27:26.478 --> 27:28.280
Oh, that's not a good sign.

27:28.314 --> 27:29.816
I don't know how to say it.

27:29.849 --> 27:31.517
It's, "Sorry, Pops."

27:31.550 --> 27:34.286
I am in better shape
than you to do it.

27:34.320 --> 27:36.155
That's for sure.
Yeah.

27:36.188 --> 27:38.691
- And I don't want to be mean.
- I'm not doing it.

27:41.728 --> 27:44.196
♪

27:44.230 --> 27:46.365
So what's
the most common injury?

27:46.398 --> 27:49.736
So, a lot of knee and shoulders,

27:49.769 --> 27:51.537
dislocated shoulders.

27:51.570 --> 27:53.339
- Head injuries.
- Concussion?

27:53.372 --> 27:55.207
- Concussion.
- Yes.

27:55.241 --> 27:57.376
I mean, I noticed,
you know, there's a bar here.

27:57.409 --> 28:01.213
I mean, do... how stupid
do people get on the mountain?

28:01.247 --> 28:02.648
You would be very surprised.

28:02.681 --> 28:07.586
We see people not trained,
not well-equipped,

28:07.619 --> 28:09.221
following, like, ski tracks

28:09.255 --> 28:12.524
to get them to crevasses,
glaciers, cracks.

28:12.558 --> 28:15.594
Right. So, if he drinks
two bottles of Génépi,

28:15.627 --> 28:19.365
and he goes off piece...

28:20.733 --> 28:22.835
And falls into a crevasse...

28:22.869 --> 28:25.271
Ahh!

28:25.304 --> 28:27.173
Dislocates his shoulder...

28:27.206 --> 28:28.274
Augh!

28:28.307 --> 28:29.341
Breaks his knee...

28:29.375 --> 28:30.409
Ahh!

28:30.442 --> 28:31.677
And...

28:31.710 --> 28:33.412
- Why me?
- Has a concussion...

28:33.445 --> 28:35.414
This is a hypothetical question.
Okay, okay.

28:35.447 --> 28:38.684
So, okay,
hypothermia is setting in.

28:38.717 --> 28:43.255
Your ACL and your meniscus
are both completely shredded,

28:44.924 --> 28:46.625
And your all messed up
from a concussion...

28:48.928 --> 28:50.562
What is the thing I...
I should do?

28:50.596 --> 28:52.631
Should I ski to the bottom
and talk to someone?

28:52.664 --> 28:54.266
- Yeah.
- Like, call my cell phone?

28:54.300 --> 28:56.302
First I'd call
the production company

28:56.335 --> 28:57.930
and tell them we need somebody
else for the rest of the show.

28:57.937 --> 28:59.738
He's such a nice guy.

28:59.772 --> 29:01.466
To answer your question there,
there is something today

29:01.473 --> 29:03.810
we use more and more
on the people's cell phones.

29:03.843 --> 29:05.644
Oh, find my phone.

29:05.677 --> 29:07.479
- Find my corpse.
- Find my phone.

29:07.513 --> 29:09.816
And just ask the people,
"Okay go back to your phone,

29:09.849 --> 29:11.818
"and there's a GPS inside it,

29:11.851 --> 29:13.719
and it tells us
exactly where to find you."

29:15.487 --> 29:17.924
Avalanches happen here
frequently.

29:17.957 --> 29:20.927
Laurent and his rescue squads
are here to prevent them

29:20.960 --> 29:22.995
before they occur if possible,

29:23.029 --> 29:26.465
and if not, to find you,
and dig you out.

29:26.498 --> 29:28.667
Allow us to demonstrate.

29:28.700 --> 29:31.737
We bury our local contact,
Bullet, under the snow.

29:31.770 --> 29:33.639
Search dogs, hopefully,

29:33.672 --> 29:35.975
will find him
before he becomes a corpsicle

29:36.008 --> 29:39.411
and our production insurance
becomes unsustainably expensive.

29:42.448 --> 29:42.948
♪

29:49.455 --> 29:51.023
So, how common are avalanche?

29:51.057 --> 29:53.692
Where are they most
likely to... to happen?

29:53.725 --> 29:55.694
Anywhere but the ski resorts.

29:55.727 --> 29:59.465
Mostly the avalanches that kills
people is not into a ski resort.

29:59.498 --> 30:00.699
It's...
Outside.

30:00.732 --> 30:01.868
Outside the boundaries.

30:01.901 --> 30:03.635
Now, here's a question.

30:03.669 --> 30:05.604
Ugh, great.

30:05.637 --> 30:07.306
So, Eric's come back after

30:07.339 --> 30:09.375
he's recovered
from his injuries,

30:09.408 --> 30:14.280
and he decides
to go mountain climbing.

30:14.313 --> 30:16.282
And he gets drunk again.

30:16.315 --> 30:18.317
Something happened to me,
you're gonna remember,

30:18.350 --> 30:20.012
I'll tell you that.
And he climbs the mountain.

30:20.019 --> 30:21.787
Ahh!

30:21.820 --> 30:23.455
And he gets buried
in this avalanche.

30:25.024 --> 30:26.825
And he's buried in the snow.

30:27.994 --> 30:29.628
What happens then?

30:29.661 --> 30:34.400
Or, do you just say,
"Eh, see you in the summer."

30:34.433 --> 30:36.087
Well, first you have
to find the location,

30:36.102 --> 30:38.905
the whole location, and then we
have a Tran signal locator

30:38.938 --> 30:40.565
like this one, as an example.
Something like this.

30:40.572 --> 30:42.041
- Yes.
- And when you are caught

30:42.074 --> 30:43.910
in the avalanche...
They look for it.

30:43.943 --> 30:46.712
The rest of teams keep a tool
working with the same one,

30:46.745 --> 30:49.381
and then they can find a signal,
and then they start digging.

30:49.415 --> 30:51.110
How long can you live
under the snow? If it's not...

30:51.117 --> 30:52.985
You have three minutes.

30:53.019 --> 30:54.386
Three minutes for...

30:54.420 --> 30:56.022
Three minutes if you can press.

30:56.055 --> 30:58.590
- Right.
- But sometimes, you have

30:58.624 --> 31:00.893
a little place for breathing.

31:00.927 --> 31:02.694
- A little room?
- Yes,

31:02.728 --> 31:06.098
and you can survive
a half an hour, one hour.

31:06.132 --> 31:07.666
So I shouldn't give up too soon.

31:07.699 --> 31:08.834
Yes.

31:11.870 --> 31:12.370
♪

33:01.747 --> 33:03.782
So, why did you choose
such a dangerous

33:03.815 --> 33:05.784
and difficult area of medicine?

33:05.817 --> 33:07.819
I mean, you could have
a nice practice in Paris,

33:07.853 --> 33:09.148
got, you know,
people have headaches.

33:09.155 --> 33:10.622
It's difficult to explain.

33:13.659 --> 33:14.159
♪

33:17.829 --> 33:21.133
Yes, I know it's very dangerous,

33:21.167 --> 33:23.702
but, I think,

33:23.735 --> 33:25.704
"I have to continue;
I have to stop."

33:25.737 --> 33:28.474
I... I continue.

33:28.507 --> 33:31.210
♪

33:31.243 --> 33:35.047
I'm not sure why I do it, but
I know it makes me alive, so...

33:35.081 --> 33:37.483
it's good.
But you like it.

33:37.516 --> 33:38.717
- I do like it.
- Yeah, right?

33:38.750 --> 33:40.219
♪

33:40.252 --> 33:42.888
You don't think about that.

33:42.921 --> 33:44.756
You don't know why,
but you do it.

33:44.790 --> 33:45.891
Mm-hmm.

33:45.924 --> 33:48.594
That's called compassion.

33:51.630 --> 33:52.130
♪

34:08.246 --> 34:12.016
Le France, I love it, and God
knows I love the cheese here,

34:12.050 --> 34:13.784
but a brief respite is needed

34:13.819 --> 34:15.853
from the torrent
of dairy products.

34:15.887 --> 34:18.889
Perhaps, I thought, the short
hop across the border to Italy,

34:18.924 --> 34:20.792
would be a good idea.

34:20.826 --> 34:22.728
I want pasta.

34:22.761 --> 34:26.232
Maison Recettes has a long
and storied history here

